subsection.p:
In coordinates,
\boxed{\Delta u=u_{xx}+u_{yy}}
in the plane, and
\boxed{\Delta u=u_{xx}+u_{yy}+u_{zz}}
in space.

There is also a forms version. In the plane, the flux form of the gradient field 
abla u=(u_x,u_y) is  oxed{\phi_{
abla u}=u_x\,dy-u_y\,dx.} Then
d\phi_{
abla u} \amp= d(u_x\,dy-u_y\,dx) \amp= u_{xx}\,dx\wedge dy-u_{yy}\,dy\wedge dx \amp= (u_{xx}+u_{yy})\,dx\wedge dy \amp= \Delta u\,dx\wedge dy.
So  oxed{d\phi_{
abla u}=\Delta u\,dx\wedge dy.}

In space, the flux form of \nabla u is
\boxed{\Phi_{\nabla u}=u_x\,dy\wedge dz+u_y\,dz\wedge dx+u_z\,dx\wedge dy.}
Its exterior derivative is
\boxed{d\Phi_{\nabla u}=\Delta u\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.}

statement.p:
A twice differentiable function u is called harmonic on a region D if
\boxed{\Delta u=0}
at every point of D.

subsection.p:
A harmonic function has a gradient field with no source inside the region: 
abla\cdot(
abla u)=0. Equivalently, d\Phi_{
abla u}=0 in space, or d\phi_{
abla u}=0 in the plane.

statement.p:
Let u be C^2 on a region D. Then u is harmonic on D if and only if,
for every small solid region E\subset D,
\boxed{\int_{\partial E}\Phi_{\nabla u}=0.}
In the plane, the corresponding statement is
\boxed{\int_{\partial R}\phi_{\nabla u}=0}
for every small plane region R\subset D.

subsection.p:
First see it in a concrete example. Let u(x,y)=x^2-y^2. Take a circle of radius r centered at (a,b): x=a+r\cos\theta,\qquad y=b+r\sin\theta. Then
u(a+r\cos\theta,b+r\sin\theta) \amp= (a+r\cos\theta)^2-(b+r\sin\theta)^2 \amp= a^2-b^2+2ar\cos\theta-2br\sin\theta \amp\qquad +r^2(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta).
Average from 0 to 2\pi. The average of \cos\theta is 0, the average of \sin\theta is 0, and the average of \cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta=\cos(2\theta) is also 0. So the circular average is a^2-b^2. But u(a,b)=a^2-b^2. Thus \boxed{\text{average of }u\text{ on the circle}=u\text{ at the center.}}

image.latex-image:
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9, >=stealth]
    \draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (5.2,0) node[right] {\(x\)};
    \draw[->] (0,-0.5) -- (0,4.3) node[above] {\(y\)};

    \coordinate (C) at (2.7,2.0);
    \draw[thick, blue!60!black] (C) circle (1.25);

    \fill (C) circle (2.5pt);
    \node[below left] at (C) {\((a,b)\)};

    \draw[->, thick] (C) -- ++(0.9,0.87)
        node[midway, above left] {\(r\)};

    \node at (2.7,-0.9)
        {\(\displaystyle u(a,b)=\frac1{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi}
        u(a+r\cos\theta,b+r\sin\theta)\,d\theta\)};
\end{tikzpicture}

proof.p:
Let A(r)= rac1{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi}u(a+r\cos	heta,b+r\sin	heta)\,d	heta. Differentiate with respect to r: A'(r)= rac1{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi}
abla u\cdot(\cos	heta,\sin	heta)\,d	heta. On the circle of radius r, the outward unit normal is \widehat{\mathbf n}=(\cos	heta,\sin	heta), and ds=r\,d	heta. So A'(r)= rac1{2\pi r}\int_{C_r}
abla u\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}\,ds. By the divergence theorem in the plane, \int_{C_r}
abla u\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}\,ds=\iint_{D_r}\Delta u\,dA. Since u is harmonic, \Delta u=0, so A'(r)=0. Thus A(r) is constant as r changes. As r	o0, the circle shrinks to the point (a,b), and by continuity A(r)	o u(a,b). Therefore every A(r) equals u(a,b).

statement.p:
For a differentiable function u on a plane region R, the Dirichlet energy
of u is
\boxed{\mathcal E[u]=\frac12\iint_R |\nabla u|^2\,dA.}

subsection.md:
\begin{array}{c|l}
\text{View} & \text{Meaning} \\ \hline
\Delta u=0 & \text{no local source for the gradient field}\\[1mm]
\displaystyle \int_{\partial R}\phi_{\nabla u}=0
& \text{zero gradient flux through every small boundary}\\[3mm]
u(a,b)=\text{circle average} & \text{perfect local balance}\\[1mm]
\mathcal E[u]\text{ is minimal} & \text{least energy among fixed boundary values}
\end{array}
